"    These illustrations highlight the characteristics of the stages of pressure ulcers as defined by the National Pressure Ulcer Advisory Panel. Each panel demonstrates the clinical appearance of the involved skin as well as the cross section of the depth of injury. Most pressure ulcers are associated with an underlying bony prominence. As illustrated by Suspected deep tissue injury, there is always the potential for deeper tissue damage than originally appreciated. This is due to the \"tip of the iceberg\" phenomenon, as soft tissues are more susceptible to injury than skin.",
